<br>
- Sure, it is safer to sava mana IN battle then BEFORE battle, but think of all the things you summon now post PoP : weapons, belt, etc etc. In the long run, you use your Conj spells much more ...<br>
<br>
Final note about Sun Storm : this spell is really NICE and becomes even much more mana efficient than Firebolt of Tallon when you group with a druid who uses his fire debuff. Malosini(a)ed + fire debuffed, it is very frequent to get three full waves ... and with SCF 3 + FoM 1 (so guess FoM 2 and 3 ...) it happens from time to time to get 2 crits on one rain.<br>
Yesterday ion a blue to 62 mob, malosinied and fire debuffed, I got 1600 + 800 + 1600 = 4000, so about a critted bolt with less mana, he he... and best : pet kept aggro without any problem.<br>
<br>
Elemental Specializings ! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jochangaladar>Jochan Galadar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Gospel According to St. Jochan</span><br>  Posts: 969<br> <font color=#333333>(3/5/03 5:32:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=565.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: If i am not a cannipetting mage is switch to Evoc. best </span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I understand and respect the arguments in favor of evocation<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The evocation approach is the oldest approach magicians have access to.  At level 1, we have nothing but nukes.  We add a pet at level 4, but its dps and dpm pales next to our dmg spell arsenal.  We can add in our ds at level 8.  It really isn't until level 12 and our first Burnout spell that pet dps starts to become respectable in comparison to nukes.<br>
<br>
Such is the way of the Magician until at least level 29, and usually 34.  The pets stop increasing their mana demands to summon, and their tanking ability and damage dealing increases in both quantity and mana efficiency.  This is the point where the option to chain truly begins.  Nukes take longer and longer to cast, and cost more and more mana, while the pets continue to stay at 200 mana until level 51, and take the same amount of time to summon.<br>
<br>
Moving on at 51, chaining is at its most viable, with a pet that outtanks and outdamages every pet before it.  It is the bread and butter chaining pet.  It is mana efficient, a respectable tank, and relatively easy and inexpensive to replace on the fly.  It requires no special gear, nor any special mana regeneration, but it gets the job done, without seriously draining the precious mana supplies.  This is a good thing for the more casual folks who are not &quot;gear happy,&quot; &quot;uber,&quot; or &quot;rich.&quot;<br>
<br>
  On the other side of things, there are those who would prefer to hyperextend the old ways, the level 1-29 evocation standby, and yet realize that the pets handed to us are not ideal for this.  Enter the &quot;elite&quot; world of the Magician Epic, and its prodigy the Epic pet, backing it up with those nukes that suck down mana at an ever increasing pace, and taking longer and longer to cast.  With a 5 minute recast time, and a 20 second summon time, you can bet you want to keep this pet around as long as possible.  Gear is especially important here, as the emphasis is big mana pool, accelerated mana regen, and fast damage dealing.  Bring along some outside buffs as well, because you will need them.  KEI is the buff of choice, and Flowing Thought is the gear of choice.<br>
<br>
   Back to the chainers.  By level 58, the 51 pet is starting to show its age.  The mobs are not dropping as fast as they used to, but the new circle of pets are not much more efficient than the last one.....  until 59 and the Luclin AA Class skills.<br>
<br>
Enter the new order, the spanking new tactic of recycling summoning mana in order to pet tank indefinitely.  This is the next step in the chaining paradigm, that of  reclaim chaining.  Suddenly there is a great boost to soloing efficiency, and for chainers, a large boost in damage output, as you can now chain the newest circle of pets AND haste them without consuming any extra mana.  The benefits?  Equipment demands are minimal, outside buff demands are virtually nonexistent, and the time consuming &quot;Epic Quest&quot; is sidestepped.  Oh yeah, don't forget, ZERO downtime.  The drawbacks?  The evokers, with their FT gear, Epic pets, and outside clarity buffs, are dropping the mobs faster.<br>
<br>
Evokers are dropping a mob faster.  They are medding a lot more too.  The fact is, though, if you have access to the gear and the buffs, the evocation approach, as old as it is, will let you drop a mob faster, and that probably means the most to the greatest number of people.  It's easier to notice a fast kill than an efficient kill.  It's also good for the ego.<br>
<br>
Personally, I prefer a degree of independence from gear and outside help.  It helps when things go bad in a group or raid.  It makes me feel more self-assured, rather than dependent and helpless.  It's a good feeling.  I don't get that feeling bumming buffs from others or getting awarded a piece of gear in a raid.  The gear is cool, and the buffs are cool, and I'll use them when I have them, but knowing I can easily do without them  gives me a very nice peace of mind. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Grand Poobah Goladus</span><br>  Posts: 2764<br> <font color=#333333>(3/5/03 9:02:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=565.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://doug.feldmann.com/Sigurd.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: If i am not a cannipetting mage is switch to Evoc. best </span><hr size=1> I choose to stay as a conjuration mage not because I subscribe to to any one particular style.. indeed that I do not is part of my reason for remaining conjuration.  I try to stay balanced and versatile.<br>
<br>
60+<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Evocation:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Firebolt of Tallon<br>
Rains<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Conjuration:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Black Steel<br>
Sun Vortex<br>
All pets<br>
Pet heals<br>
Mod Rods<br>
Call of the Hero<br>
<br>
<br>
I find that Evocation would serve me best if I could expect to always be able to use FoT or Rains.  However if I was in a high-downtime situation, I could make up for lost nuke effeciency by better cannipet effeciency.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, conjuration benefits me in a much greater variety of situations.  In a burn down situation where I don't want a bolt or a rain, conjure will help the &quot;Evocationist&quot; style.  When I want to chain pets, conjuration will clearly benefit me.  When I am chaining in heals, conjuration will help me.  When I need to use Call of the Hero, mana will be less of an issue.  While Frenzied Transvergence is a thing of the past, I still get requests for T-rods and use them myself, and effeciency there doesn't hurt anything.  <br>
<br>
For me, conjuration benefits many combat situations of varying types.   Conjuration is the clear winner during downtime and for misc. utility.  If you cannipet, conjuration can potentially flat out make up the lost effeciency when you choose to use evocation spells in combat.<br>
<br>
In contrast, Evocation gives you optimal results for a relatively narrow range of combat experiences-- that is, relative to Black Steel, Sun Vortex, and chain-petting.  I find both bolts and rains to be unreliable..  It's true that I find reclaim-chaining to be similarly restricted, however reclaim chaining is not the only strategy that takes advantage of conjuration specialization.<br>
<br>
edit:<br>
<br>
also, in the times when I am forced to use a pre-PoP non-bolt, Shock of Fiery Blades is basically as good as it gets, and that's a conjure nuke.  The only good non-bolt, non-rain evoc spell pre-60 is Char, which isn't quite as good anymore since you can't circumvent the recast. <p><center><br>
